 characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Stayne","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Steen  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Steen","meanings":["North German, Norwegian, and Danish; Swedish (also <b>Steén</b> and <b>Stéen</b>); Dutch and Flemish (also <b>Van der Steen</b>): from Middle Low German <i>stēn</i>, Old Norse <i>steinn</i> (Danish and Swedish <i>sten</i>) ‘stone’, hence a topographic name for someone who lived on stony ground, or a metonymic occupational name for someone who worked with stone (quarryman, stonecutter, or stonemason). As a Swedish name it is mainly habitational name from a placename, such as Stenby, containing the word <i>sten</i> ‘stone’; it can also be from the personal name <i>Sten</i>, with the same meaning. Compare   Sten  .","English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Steyne</i> (Old Norse <i>Steinn</i>, <i>Sten</i>, meaning ‘stone’).","English: habitational name from any of various minor places in northern England and Scotland named with Old English <i>stān</i> ‘stone, rock’ (northern Middle English <i>stayn</i>), or in the rest of England with Old English <i>stǣne</i> ‘stony place’ (Middle English <i>stane</i>, <i>stayne</i>, <i>stene</i>), including Steane (Northamptonshire), Stein Farm in East Dean (Sussex), Stains in Funtington (Sussex), what is now Old Steine in Brighton (Sussex), and Steyne in Chale (Isle of Wight). Compare   Staines  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":5,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705192,"age":18,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705195,"age":72,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"William De Stayne was born about 1310, in Yorkshire, England as the son of Stayn and Mrs Stayn. He married Mrs William de STAYNE about 1330, in Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"about 1310–":"umbes 1310–Surnud","1310–Male":"1310–Surnud","1310–Female":"1310–Surnud","1330–1375":"1330–1375","–Male":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1315":"1315","ABT 1330":"umbes 1330","1310":"1310","1375":"1375","1330":"1330","about 1310":"umbes 1310","1382":"1382","about 1330":"umbes 1330","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Stayne, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Marblethorpe, Lincoln, England":"Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Mablethorpe, Lincolnshire, England Place":"Mablethorpe, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1310–":"noin 1310–Kuollut","1310–Male":"1310–Kuollut","1310–Female":"1310–Kuollut","1330–1375":"1330–1375","–Male":"Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1315":"1315","ABT 1330":"noin 1330","1310":"1310","1375":"1375","1330":"1330","about 1310":"noin 1310","1382":"1382","about 1330":"noin 1330","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Stayne, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Marblethorpe, Lincoln, England":"Lincolnshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Mablethorpe, Lincolnshire, England Place":"Mablethorpe, Lincolnshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1310–":"environ 1310–Décédé","1310–Male":"1310–Décédé","1310–Female":"1310–Décédée","1330–1375":"1330–1375","–Male":"Décédé","–Female":"Décédée","1315":"1315","ABT 1330":"environ 1330","1310":"1310","1375":"1375","1330":"1330","about 1310":"environ 1310","1382":"1382","about 1330":"environ 1330","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Stayne, Yorkshire, England":"Everwyck, Angleterre","Marblethorpe, Lincoln, England":"Lincolnshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Mablethorpe, Lincolnshire, England Place":"Mablethorpe, Lincolnshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"William De Stayne est n